No heals for j00~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/usiggymk5.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SiggyMk5</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Led Ezra</span><br>  Posts: 2301<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/20/02 10:25:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1642.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.in-your-ear.net/rejkid.gif  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lol</span><hr size=1> Well, Caramor, I'm feeling a little bored so I'm going to do a point-by-point to explain how this isn't me and how these views are bad for -any- country.<br>
<br>
--***--<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I like big cars, big boats, big motorcycles, big houses, and big campfires. I believe the money I make belongs to me and my family, not some governmental stooge with a bad comb-over who wants to give it away to crack addicts for squirting out babies.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Big cars, boats and motorcycles, eh?  That's one of the big ways we got in our current environmental mess, especially in cities like Los Angeles, but more importantly it's our absolute reliance on these types of vehicles and unwillingness to change that makes us so willing to be friendly with oil-rich nations like Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, UAE, etc.  I suppose it's fine to &quot;like&quot; these things, but unfortunately our inability to &quot;like&quot; alternatives is morally rotting our nation to the core.<br>
<br>
-That money you make... sure it belongs to you but its not like the government isn't using it for important things.  You like having National Security, pay your taxes.  You like your children having access to education, parks and public events, pay your taxes.  You like having roads to drive your gas-guzzling big car on, pay your taxes.  You like having legal recourse for when you get screwed, pay your taxes.  As for the pork barrel and inefficiency of government, firstly it varies hugely from location to location and organization to organization and secondly its from YOUR ELECTED OFFICIALS.  The government exists to enable the people, not repress them.  And, I'm sorry, but American taxes aren't that bad at all.  Look at how incredibly high the American standard of living is compared to the rest of the world.  A lot of poorer countries and have little to no (fully enforcable) tax codes and they sure seem to be great... more Papua New Guinea if you don't want to pay taxes and then  pray the UN will be responsive to your needs as a citizen, because the Papuan government has not the means.<br>
<br>
-Crack-whores squirting out babies... So you're assuming all people on unemployment or food stamps are crack whores?  As an exmaple, both my parents have been on food stamps before at some point in their lives and are now PhD professionals.  One of the great things about modern Western governments is we don't cast-off our unfortunate into an eternal underclass.  It's that very social responsibility that keeps the American dream alive, especially if your, for example, your submarine factory closes due to government budget cuts.  Yes, there are people who take advantage of the system but the vast majority do not.  And though I don't have much sympathy for the genuine crack-whores themselves, what about their children?  Should we cast them off?  Obviously their mother isn't making the kind of money necessary to support them on her own.  The only other humane option is some sort of foster care, which is essentially doing the same thing, albeit in a more indirect way.<br>
<br>
-As for me, I like fuel-efficient and alternative energy cars, like keeping my money but realize that government with good oversight actually is a wonderful place to invest money... assuming I like things like infrastructure.  Economy of scale lets the government do it more cost-effectively than developers.  I support social welfare programs with proper government oversight.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Guns do not make you a killer. I think killing makes you a killer. You can kill someone with a baseball bat or a car, but no one is trying to ban you from driving to the ball game.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Guns don't make you a killer, but they sure as hell facilitate you if you are one... and they make it damn easy to accidentally become one.  Guns kill.  It's what they're designed to do (even if their chosen target is a deer).  Baseball bats and cars are not so designed.  To be perfectly honest, though, I've never understood this country's obsession with fire arms so I can't really make an argument against something which, to my point of view, doesn't even have an internal logic to argue against.<br>
<br>
-I don't own a gun.  I don't ever intend to.  I lobby against handguns.  Facilitating the unwise is not my cup of tea.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I believe they are called the Boy Scouts for a reason, that is why there are no girls allowed. Girls belong in the Girl Scouts.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-I'll agree on that point.  However, gays are still boys and lesbians are still girls and these organizations, as long as they're using government lands and facilities, can't be homophobic by policy.  Homosexual people have just as much need for community and the lifeskills taught by the scouts as heterosexuals.  However, they are private organizations, so as long as they're not using my tax dollars (by using public facilities) to do their business, more power to them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I think that if you feel homosexuality is wrong, it is not a phobia, it is an opinion. I don't think being a minority makes you a victim of anything except numbers. The only things I can think of that are truly discriminatory are things like the United Negro College Fund, Jet Magazine, Black Entertainment Television, and Miss Black America. Try to have things like the United Caucasian College Fund, Cloud Magazine, White Entertainment Television, or Miss White America and see what happens. Jesse Jackson will be knocking down your door.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Homosexuality:Thinking homosexuality is wrong is an opinion.  It may also be a phobia.  I frankly don't care so long as you're accepting of different people in your community and not, for example, burning crosses in their lawns or raping or murdering them.  But remember, all men (and women) are created equal in this country, so you've got no high horse or soap-box on this issue and, as members of the American community, they have all the same rights and privelages you do.<br>
<br>
-Minorities: It's too bad the US isn't culturally to the place you are where people are not discriminated against because of a race, religion, sexuality or gender.  It's intolerant and bigoted people that make minorities so caudified and seperated from the American community at large, so unless you've got a way to stop that then being a minority is gonna have to do with a lot more than numbers for a long time to come.  Basically, I agree with the general point of the author, but somehow I don't get the impression he's looking at the whole picture.<br>
<br>
-Discrimination: And why shouldn't these organizations and media exist?  There sure seems to be a market for them in our free-market system.  Perhaps these minorities have needs they're better able to address in-house.  These just has to do with your short-sighted definition of 'minority'.  Computer gamers are also a minority and they have their own media and, yes, even beauty pagents.  Scholarships exist purely for people interested in math or 1920s Yellow journalism.  Not all minorties exist along easy, phenological lines and frankly, being in a cultural minority helps your refine who you are and your place in society.  Phenological minorities are just one expression of this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I have the right &quot;NOT&quot; to be tolerant of others because they are different, weird, or tick me off. When 70% of the people who get arrested are black, in cities where 70% of the population is black, that is not racial profiling, it is the law of statistics.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Your rights, huh?  I'm sorry, you don't have the right not to be tolerant if the people who are pissing you off are your fellow Americans.  You don't have to like them.  You don't have to hang out with them.  But you damn well better be tolerant.  If you are violent or defamatory towards them you are outside the law.  Your preferences don't elevate you as an individual over someone else.  Everyone of voting age is equal in this country.  Period.  And they must all be treated with respect and dignity.<br>
<br>
-Minority profiling-There are very few major cities where African-Americans are in the majority, especially at a 70% level.  In a country where you're technically innocent until proven guilty it's odd that certain minorities seem more likely to be arrested in the first place... implying a perversion of this rule.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I know what sex is, and there are not varying degrees of it. If I received sex from one of my subordinates in my office, it wouldn't be a private matter or my personal business. I would be &quot;FIRED&quot; immediately!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Whoop-de-shit.  Have to get your Clinton pot-shit in, right?  Good for you.  Obviously you don't work for 90% of the organizations in this country... and certainly not one of its churches.  To me, if it's a concentual relationship, I don't care anyway.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I believe that if you are selling me a milk shake, a pack of cigarettes, a newspaper or a hotel room, you must do it in English. As a matter of fact, if you want to be an American citizen you should speak English. My father and grandfather shouldn't have to die in vain so you can leave the countries you were born in to come over and disrespect ours.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-We don't have a national language.  People are free to speak whatever they want.  If you don't like going to a private business where English isn't the language, take your business somewhere else.  Speaking English has nothing to do with being an American citizen.  Hell, German almost became our national language (and I don't mean during the 1940s).  Being an American citizen is about carving out your niche in a the many varied community of the States and participating in the political process.<br>
<br>
-You relatives-I'm sorry they died in war.  That sucks.  However, other people's freedom of movement likely has little to do with their deaths and does it them a service that America is still such a free country that people can immigrate and continue to mold our cultural values and viewpoint.  Freedom isn't about choosing one thing as 'right' and sticking to it, it's about having the ability to change.  You personally don't have to change, but you can't take away the rights of others to change or be different.  And if you want to get into the whole &quot;disrespecting nations&quot; issue, Americans don't come from a very strong arguing point... especially when it comes to the Americas, the Middle East and East Asia.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I think the police should have every right to shoot your sorry ass if you threaten them after they tell you to stop. If you can't understand the word &quot;freeze&quot; or &quot;stop&quot; in English, see the above lines.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-I think the above martial law comments mostly handle this issue.  As for English, not the official language, so that's not the case.  Newsflash, bro, Hispanics will soon be the -majority- in this country.  You might want to look into learning some Spanish in case your xenophobia backlashes and the Hispanic majority pushes through an official change to Spanish as our national language.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I feel much safer letting a machine with no political affiliation recount votes when needed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree.  Just make sure the machine a) works, and b) gets all the votes to it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I know what the definition of lying is.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is good.  Most people are aware of this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I don't think just because you were not born in this country, you are qualified for any special loan programs, government sponsored bank loans or tax breaks etc., so you can open a hotel, coffee shop, trinket store, or any other business.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-If you want money from the government or a tax break to do something.  Just look around, there's bound to be something to help you personally out.  Stop being so paranoid.  And why shouldn't we help immigrants melt into American culture?  How exactly is it that hurts us?  The government knows it pays huge dividends to get people mainlined into succesful fiscal and cultural living as quickly as possible.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> We did not go to the aid of certain foreign countries and risk our lives in wars to defend their freedoms so that decades later they could come over here and tell us our constitution is a living document and open to their interpretations.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Constitution should be capitalized.  Well, hmm, the Constitution -is- a living document and is certainly open to all interpretations.  We don't have to agree, but that's not the point.  I would hope our reason (though history doesn't really agree on this issue) for aiding other countries was to promote, defend and encourage their freedom and we should be honored they are taking that freedom to heart and forming opinions.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I don't hate the rich. I don't pity the poor. I know wrestling is fake, but so are movies and television, and that doesn't stop you from watching them. I believe a self-righteous liberal or conservative with a cause is more dangerous than a Hell's Angel with an attitude.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Then stop being a self-righteous conservative... unless you like being dangerous.  Because you are quite clearly in the hardcore Neocon category with the views expressed here.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I think Bill Gates has every right to keep every penny he made and continue to make more. If it ticks you off, go and invent the next operating system that's better and put your name on the building. Ask your buddy that invented the Internet to help you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Gates does have the rights to his money.  He does not, however, have the rights to monopolize the industry, squash competition and destroy the free market in his sector while extorting and robbing consumers.  Anti-monopoly laws are there to protect the capitalist way of life.  Monopolies, by definition, make it extremely hard (nigh impossible) to bring competition, even vastly superior, into the market.  What Al Gore has to do with this I have no clue.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It doesn't take a whole village to raise a child right, but it does take a parent to stand up to the kid and smack his little ass when necessary and say &quot;NO.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-&quot;Raising a child right&quot; is a very subjective thing, but violence certainly isn't the answer.  It is, however, well proven that all a child's social interactions effect their development, so the more healthy your commuity (or village, if you prefer) the better the odds the child will come out well.  Anyway, I don't see why anyone wouldn't want a healthy community.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot; I think tattoos and piercing are fine if you want them, but please don't pretend they are a political statement. And stay home until that new lip ring heals, I don't want to look at your ugly infected mouth as you serve me fries.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Okay, I won't pretend--I will know--that if I get a tattoo that says, &quot;Anarchist&quot; that it is a political statement.  What I define as political speech may be completely irrelevant to you, and that's fine.  Bear in mind that's a two-lane street.  How your interact with society and present yourself within it is inheritly political.  Your values define you.  And if you don't like the lip ring, take your business elsewhere.  Free market, remember?<br>
<br>
-I dye my hair.  Often with political intent.  Usually it's just a radical color to show my objection to mainstream America.  It was, however, red, white, &amp; blue about this time last year and that was CERTAINLY a political statement.  Piercings and tattoos are not so different.  You don't have to acknowledge those politics, but they're present regardless.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I am sick of &quot;Political Correctness&quot; and of all the suck ups that go along with it. I know a lot of black people, and not a single one of them was born in Africa, so how can they be &quot;African-Americans&quot;? Besides, Africa is a continent. I don't go around saying I am a European-American because my great, great, great, great, great, great grandfather was from Europe. I am proud to be from America and nowhere else.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-People can be proud of whatever aspect of their history they like.  It's fine for you if you're only proud of the American aspect of your heritage, but that isn't the case for everyone.  A lot of AMERICANS go around saying their &quot;Irish&quot; or &quot;German&quot; or &quot;Polish.&quot;  As for Africa being a continent, it's nice for most of us caucasian folk that we know where we're from.  It's a bit harder to keep track of that if you're stolen from your village and sailed across the ocean and sold into generations of slavery.  Call people what they want to be called.  Is that so hard?  Different people value different aspects of their heritage and I just don't see how it hurts you to be sensitive to that.<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> And if you don't like my point of view, tough!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
-Fine, but if you don't like mine, tough.  You have to tolerate it.  Welcome to America, where speech is protected and citizens have certain unalienable rights.<br>
<br>
--Sslanis<br>
