No heals for j00~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/usiggymk5.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SiggyMk5</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Led Ezra</span><br>  Posts: 2303<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/21/02 2:01:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1642.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.in-your-ear.net/rejkid.gif  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lol</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> we have the oil in america.. you wont let us drill it, who was it that made us dependant on free drilling countries?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Even if we were to drill every single -potential- oil field in the United States we wouldn't have enough oil to meet the needs of the American economy.  Do we have oil?  Yes.  Do we have enough?  No way in Hell.  Sooner or later it's going to run out anyway.  So here's an idea, how about we kill a few birds with one stone by developing (or in many cases simply implementing) alternatives to fossil fuels so that a) we are a world leader in the coming new energy economy, b) we can avoid environmentally dangerous aspects of the current economy, c) we are done with our reliance on questionable foreign leaders for oil, and d) we can finally stop arguing dosmetically about this crap.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> you didnt take the whole sentince in context, the guy dont want his money going to permanent welfare cases, sure to get people back on their feet, hey i see nothing wrong with cutting an honest guy a break, but damnit, i dont want to support the crack whores and deadbeats of the country with my hard earned cash<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There's a couple problems here.  First, it's very hard to seperate the life-long deadbeat from the unlucky or disadvantaged.  How would you make that judgement and more importantly how would do it fairly and equitably?  Second, as disgusting as it sometimes seems to provide lifelong deadbeats minimal support, it prevents them from falling into even more desperate situations like permanent homelessness and helps limit their inclination to commit crimes.<br>
<br>
Think of it this way.  We support the people in our current form or something near it--relatively, it's rather cheap, and from time-to-time even permanent deadbeats have jobs and make other contributions to the economy.  If we don't support them this way, odds are many will end up sleeping in your lawn, or, if that pisses you off, in jail.  It's very expensive to house someone in jail, we already don't have enough space and funding in our prisons and what was a minimal chance of this person making contributions or even a full return to the economy is now nil.<br>
<br>
Both options suck, but to my mind one is clearly superior.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> good for you im glad you like toy cars that will get you killed in a crash, me i want something that will protect my children when we get hit by something bigger then we are, oh yeah, just cuz you like something dont mean i gotta, this is america remember?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There's an odd and completely unfounded belief that fuel-economic cars are unsafe.  This is totally unfounded.  Many of them, especially because of the market they currently target (left-wingers and corporations, for the most part) are extremely concerned about safety for personal and liability reasons.  Most (but not all) aren't particularly sporty or gutsy, but for everyday driving that's not a big issue.  <br>
<br>
And hey, maybe if we got over this SUV trip we're on in the States right now, people will start driving normal sized cars and not be worried about one of the gazillion SUVs hitting them and killing their children.  After all, it's not like that SUV is gonna be much better if you get hit by a semi.<br>
<br>
Yes, it is a free country, so drive what you like.  I won't force you into a Prius or a smart.  I just believe there are so many good arguments for changing our current trajectory that I don't see how anyone can look at all the information available and not see the sense in a change.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> yep they facilitate ya if ya are one, and they facilitate me scareing off the punk who has one pointed in my direction if i point one back at him, dont forget hes a criminal, he dont care if you make a law taking his gun away, hell get one anyway, and if we dont kill the deer in a quick and clean fashion with the guns, they will starve to death in the winter, dunno about you, but id rather be shot then starve to death, as for your lobbying, lobby away, thankfully the constitution which you hold so dear aint gonna let you get away with it<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Perhaps if guns weren't legal you couldn't get one at every single pawn shop if you were a criminal.  Yes, connected and hardened criminals would still be able to find firearms if they were illegal, but if you simply couldn't buy them, anywhere, it would be more difficult for some random &quot;punk&quot; to acquire.  Illegal firearms means less access for everyone, including criminals.<br>
<br>
Necessary herd trimming is, by the way, an entirely different issue and it pisses me off when gun lobbyists try to paint it as the same picture.  To me, it's another argument for another time.<br>
<br>
And the Constitution, my interpretation of it (or the Ten Amendments if you want to be precise) doesn't hold with the right of individuals to bear firearms.  The language is ambiguous.  I'm not saying my interpretation is the right one, but it's one I'm willing to argue on.  For the sake of brevity, I will not go into it in-depth right now, though.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> YOUR tax dollars????? WTF those arent YOUR tax dollars... those tax dollars are the property of the USA and who gave you the right to decide how they get used? did you get a vote in congress recently? i mean heck... you get to use those tax dollars to dope up your crack whores, i can use them to fund my boys only clubs if i want to. (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> ed: last sentence regarding Boy Scouts</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I have three (and rarely four) votes in Congress.  I have two senators, elected to defend my rights and do what is best for the people of my State and the country, one representitive, with similar goals, and in the case of a tie I have the Vice President, elected to do the will of the People.  Everytime the House or Senate makes a vote, I am voting.<br>
<br>
This is democracy which means that the government is not a seperate entity from the People as in a, for example, monarchy.  The government taxes and holds the public's money in trust that it can provide for them certain things.  It's like the government is a large company and all voters have 1 share.  We elect a board to run our nation (in the forms of elected officials) and we give them input throughout their tenure.  If they piss us off, we fire them and replace them.  Though we don't always have direct control over what occurs, it is always OUR money.  We have to organize to be heard sometimes, but that's fair as a single person in a nation of near 300 million shouldn't be able to determine its fate alone.<br>
<br>
Regarding the boys-only club (Boy Scouts), I'm all for them being government supported (through facilities usage and whatnot) assuming they let in ALL boys.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> noones saying they shouldnt exist, but its awfully discriminitory that if i decided to air a whites entertainment network or a cloud magazine id get condemed <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You think BET, Oxygen and Lifetime don't get tons of shit and condemnations?  They still survive because there's a market for them.  If you want to make Caucasian Entertainment Television, feel free.  Despite the condemnations if there's a market for it you will succeed.  However, the likely reason you would not is because most mainstream television is still aimed at the American majority--whites.  All the major networks are, if you will, Majority Entertainment Television.  If there was a real need for a caucasian network to speak to the needs of caucasians in ways the mainstream does not, I'm sure it would appear.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> everyone of voting age is NOT equal, govt workers are not allowed to demonstrate everyone else is, non natural born citizens cannot become president, and felons cannot vote, all of these people are not equal, and illegal immigrants are also not equal, they dont even deserve to be here<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Disregarding the presidency issue (very few people I think really want to be president), all eligible people of voting age are equal.  They have one vote.  Government workers (and some others) do indeed have certain restrictions on the outward voicing of their views but in the end there's only one physical manifestation of a view in American politics, the vote, and in that regard all are equal.<br>
<br>
But even those without a political voice are generally guaranteed the same, if not similar rights (illegal immigrants, temporary and permanent residents being the primary exceptions).  My point, however, was that when it comes to respect and dignity in treatment, everyone deserves it.  It's an unspoken belief of the American way and is evidenced by the vote, which in theory is completely ignorant of race, gender, sexuality and culture.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> you know what an intern is right? a student... and the &quot;boss&quot; is her teacher while shes an intern... if a teacher has sex, consentual or otherwise with a student that teacher/professor is FIRED nuff said<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, exact policies differ very much from institution to institution and though while professor/student relations are generally frowned upon, they are not universally forbidden.<br>
<br>
In the end it's about the power dynamic.  Because the superior has control over certain aspects of the inferiors' life, there is a question of true consentuality and quid pro quo.  These are legitimate concerns, however, they are not necessarily always problems.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> there are plenty of other of your points i disagree with, however im tired and im going to bed now now <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sleep well.<br>
<br>
